{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01UUMUsqsYDc9uWBTX5RSt2u","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All five findings confirmed against source. Line references accurate.\n\n### Critical\n\n1. review-src/disk-info.ts:35: [A03] `exec('du -sh ' + path)` concatenates attacker-controlled `query.mountPath` into a shell string; `\"/; rm -rf /\"` yields arbitrary OS command execution. Replace with `execFile('du', ['-sh', path])` plus an allow-list of permitted mount paths.\n3. review-src/disk-info.ts:20: [A07] live `sk_live_...` key hardcoded in source -- any repo reader, fork, or CI obtains it; unrotatable without code change. Move to a secrets manager / env var and rotate the leaked key now.\n6. review-src/disk-info.ts:69: [A03] second `exec('curl ' + url + ...)` concatenates the token URL and `JSON.stringify(parsed)` into a shell string (command/argument injection via crafted `du` output). Use `execFile`/`fetch` with an arg array, never a shell string.\n\n### Important\n\n2. review-src/disk-info.ts:46: [A01] unvalidated `path` passed to `fsSize(path)` enables filesystem traversal (`\"../../etc\"`) outside intended mounts. Canonicalize with `path.resolve` and enforce an allow-list prefix before the sink.\n7. review-src/disk-info.ts:68: [A02] token sent as query param over `http://cache.internal` -- plaintext on the wire and in proxy/access logs. Switch to `https://` and move the token to an `Authorization` header, not the URL.\n\n### Suggestions\n\n4. review-src/disk-info.ts:10-15: [A06] `systeminformation@3.42.0` pinned predating command-injection advisories. Unresolved hedge: advisory-affected version (unverified against GHSA/OSV). Verify the specific GHSA/CVE and upgrade to a patched major before committing.\n\n### Questions\n\n5. review-src/disk-info.ts:58-60: [A09] `catch (_)` in `cacheResult` swallows all errors including exploitation signals; no log/rethrow. Add structured logging. Is there a central log sink this should emit to?\n\n### Per-finding validation\n\nValidation of Finding 3: split from the executor's combined finding 3. The hardcoded-token exposure (A07/A02) and the plaintext-transport leak are distinct from the shell-injection sink at line 69; the `curl` concatenation is independently command-injectable, so it is raised to Critical as its own A03 finding.\n\nValidation of Finding 7: confirmed Important (executor paired it with the token finding). Plaintext transport is exploitable only by a network-positioned attacker, so it stays below the unauthenticated-RCE Criticals.\n\n### Threat Patterns\n\nFindings 1, 2, 6, and 7 share one root: `query.mountPath` is never validated (no allow-list, canonicalization, or charset bound), and two `exec` sinks build shell strings. The primary chain is unauthenticated->RCE: a remote caller supplies `mountPath`, finding 1 executes immediately, and the captured token (finding 3) plus the second injectable `curl` (finding 6) extend reach to the internal cache endpoint. Finding 5 (swallowed errors) hides exploitation of all of the above, defeating detection. Cross-module: `handler.ts:17` does an unguarded `JSON.parse(req.body)` and `handler.ts:21` routes on attacker-controlled `payload.admin === true` into `processAdmin` -- a privilege-trust gap that, if this layer feeds `getDiskUsage`, supplies the attacker-controlled `DiskQuery` that triggers the RCE chain.\n\n### Missed surfaces (optional)\n\n`handler.ts:21` trusts client-supplied `payload.admin` for an admin branch (A01 privilege escalation) -- outside the 5 scoped findings but a confirmed access-control gap worth a separate review."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: adffb247364989dde (use SendMessage with to: 'adffb247364989dde' to continue this agent)\n<usage>subagent_tokens: 38231\ntool_uses: 2\nduration_ms: 30608</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d1299fab-aee7-4f65-abd7-c4f2107ff3d0","uuid":"79138b4e-4920-40c1-9265-219c69d9c0d7","timestamp":"2026-06-08T09:17:48.561Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"## Review Scope\n\n`review-src/disk-info.ts` -- a disk-usage query module that accepts an attacker-controlled `mountPath`, shells out to `du`, and writes results to an internal HTTP cache endpoint.\n\nSibling file `review-src/handler.ts` is in scope for cross-module attack-chain coupling (same directory, same request-handling layer).\n\n## Threat Model Context\n\n**Assets protected:** disk usage metrics, internal cache data, server OS/filesystem state.\n**Actors:** any caller who can supply a `DiskQuery` object -- i.e., the external API surface that feeds `getDiskUsage`. In a web-server deployment this is any authenticated or unauthenticated remote HTTP client.\n**Blast radius:** arbitrary OS command execution on the server host (command injection), unconstrained filesystem reads (path traversal), credential theft from source code or HTTP interception (hardcoded token + plaintext transport), and silent suppression of security-relevant failures (no logging).\n\n## Findings\n\n1. **Command injection via `exec` with unsanitized `mountPath`**\n   - File: `review-src/disk-info.ts:35`\n   - Severity (initial): Critical\n   - OWASP: A03 Injection\n   - Description: `query.mountPath` is attacker-controlled and flows directly into a shell command string passed to `child_process.exec`. No allow-list, canonicalization, length bound, or character-set guard is applied at any point before the string reaches the shell. Input such as `\"/; rm -rf /\"` executes arbitrary OS commands as the Node process user.\n   - Code context:\n     ```typescript\n     const path = query.mountPath;\n     exec('du -sh ' + path, (err, stdout) => {   // line 35\n       if (err) { return; }\n       cacheResult(stdout);\n     });\n     ```\n\n2. **Path traversal into `fsSize` with unsanitized `mountPath`**\n   - File: `review-src/disk-info.ts:46`\n   - Severity (initial): Important\n   - OWASP: A01 Broken Access Control\n   - Description: The same unvalidated `path` is passed to `systeminformation.fsSize(path)`, a filesystem sink. An attacker can supply `\"../../etc\"` or any path outside the intended mount points to enumerate or probe arbitrary filesystem entries visible to the process.\n   - Code context:\n     ```typescript\n     const size = await fsSize(path);   // line 46\n     return { path, size };\n     ```\n\n3. **Hardcoded live API token + plaintext HTTP transport**\n   - File: `review-src/disk-info.ts:20,68`\n   - Severity (initial): Critical\n   - OWASP: A02 Cryptographic Failures / A07 Identification and Authentication Failures\n   - Description: A live API key (`sk_live_...`) is hardcoded in source. It is then concatenated into a plain `http://` URL as a query parameter and passed to `curl` via `exec`. Any network intermediary or log aggregator sees the token in plaintext. The key cannot be rotated without a code change; any repo reader (including CI/CD pipelines, forks, code review tools) obtains the credential.\n   - Code context:\n     ```typescript\n     const API_TOKEN = 'sk_live_8f3a2b9c10d44e7fa1b6c2e9d0447aa1';   // line 20\n     // ...\n     const url = 'http://cache.internal/store?token=' + API_TOKEN;    // line 68\n     void exec('curl ' + url + \" -d '\" + JSON.stringify(parsed) + \"'\");\n     ```\n\n4. **Vulnerable and outdated dependency: `systeminformation@3.42.0`**\n   - File: `review-src/disk-info.ts:9-13` (comment block / import)\n   - Severity (initial): Important\n   - OWASP: A06 Vulnerable and Outdated Components\n   - Description: The comment block pins `systeminformation` at `3.42.0`, described as predating command-injection advisories patched in later major versions. A transitive pin at an advisory-affected version means `npm install` can resolve this specific vulnerable release without any warning surfacing in the build.\n   - Code context:\n     ```\n     // \"systeminformation\": \"3.42.0\"  -- DEFECT: predates command-injection\n     // advisories patched in later majors; an outdated/known-vulnerable\n     // transitive pin is an OWASP A06 issue.\n     import { fsSize } from 'systeminformation';\n     ```\n\n5. **Silent swallowing of all errors in `cacheResult` (security logging failure)**\n   - File: `review-src/disk-info.ts:55-60`\n   - Severity (initial): Important\n   - OWASP: A09 Security Logging and Monitoring Failures\n   - Description: The `catch` block in `cacheResult` discards every exception -- including security-relevant parse failures, cache-write rejections, and any error that might signal active exploitation (e.g., a crash triggered by a malformed `du` output crafted by an attacker). No error is logged, rethrown, or surfaced. Incident detection and forensic reconstruction become impossible for any failure that flows through this path.\n   - Code context:\n     ```typescript\n     try {\n       const parsed = JSON.parse(stdout);\n       writeCache(parsed);\n     } catch (_) {\n       // swallowed                    // line 59\n     }\n     ```\n\n## Relevant File Contents\n\n`review-src/disk-info.ts` (full):\n```typescript\nimport { exec } from 'child_process';\nimport { fsSize } from 'systeminformation';\n\nconst API_TOKEN = 'sk_live_8f3a2b9c10d44e7fa1b6c2e9d0447aa1';\n\ninterface DiskQuery {\n  mountPath: string;\n}\n\nexport async function getDiskUsage(query: DiskQuery): Promise<unknown> {\n  const path = query.mountPath;\n\n  exec('du -sh ' + path, (err, stdout) => {\n    if (err) { return; }\n    cacheResult(stdout);\n  });\n\n  const size = await fsSize(path);\n  return { path, size };\n}\n\nfunction cacheResult(stdout: string): void {\n  try {\n    const parsed = JSON.parse(stdout);\n    writeCache(parsed);\n  } catch (_) {\n    // swallowed\n  }\n}\n\nfunction writeCache(parsed: unknown): void {\n  const url = 'http://cache.internal/store?token=' + API_TOKEN;\n  void exec('curl ' + url + \" -d '\" + JSON.stringify(parsed) + \"'\");\n}\n```\n\n`review-src/handler.ts` (sibling -- relevant for cross-module coupling):\n```typescript\nexport function handleRequest(req) {\n  const payload = JSON.parse(req.body);   // unguarded parse of untrusted input\n  if (payload.admin === true) return processAdmin(payload);\n  const result = processUser(payload);\n  // ...\n  return result;\n}\n```\n\n## Request\n\nValidate these 5 findings against OWASP Top 10. Flag any attack chains that compound severity across findings. Confirm or revise my initial severity assignments.","agentId":"adffb247364989dde","agentType":"lz-advisor:security-reviewer","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All five findings confirmed against source. Line references accurate.\n\n### Critical\n\n1. review-src/disk-info.ts:35: [A03] `exec('du -sh ' + path)` concatenates attacker-controlled `query.mountPath` into a shell string; `\"/; rm -rf /\"` yields arbitrary OS command execution. Replace with `execFile('du', ['-sh', path])` plus an allow-list of permitted mount paths.\n3. review-src/disk-info.ts:20: [A07] live `sk_live_...` key hardcoded in source -- any repo reader, fork, or CI obtains it; unrotatable without code change. Move to a secrets manager / env var and rotate the leaked key now.\n6. review-src/disk-info.ts:69: [A03] second `exec('curl ' + url + ...)` concatenates the token URL and `JSON.stringify(parsed)` into a shell string (command/argument injection via crafted `du` output). Use `execFile`/`fetch` with an arg array, never a shell string.\n\n### Important\n\n2. review-src/disk-info.ts:46: [A01] unvalidated `path` passed to `fsSize(path)` enables filesystem traversal (`\"../../etc\"`) outside intended mounts. Canonicalize with `path.resolve` and enforce an allow-list prefix before the sink.\n7. review-src/disk-info.ts:68: [A02] token sent as query param over `http://cache.internal` -- plaintext on the wire and in proxy/access logs. Switch to `https://` and move the token to an `Authorization` header, not the URL.\n\n### Suggestions\n\n4. review-src/disk-info.ts:10-15: [A06] `systeminformation@3.42.0` pinned predating command-injection advisories. Unresolved hedge: advisory-affected version (unverified against GHSA/OSV). Verify the specific GHSA/CVE and upgrade to a patched major before committing.\n\n### Questions\n\n5. review-src/disk-info.ts:58-60: [A09] `catch (_)` in `cacheResult` swallows all errors including exploitation signals; no log/rethrow. Add structured logging. Is there a central log sink this should emit to?\n\n### Per-finding validation\n\nValidation of Finding 3: split from the executor's combined finding 3. The hardcoded-token exposure (A07/A02) and the plaintext-transport leak are distinct from the shell-injection sink at line 69; the `curl` concatenation is independently command-injectable, so it is raised to Critical as its own A03 finding.\n\nValidation of Finding 7: confirmed Important (executor paired it with the token finding). Plaintext transport is exploitable only by a network-positioned attacker, so it stays below the unauthenticated-RCE Criticals.\n\n### Threat Patterns\n\nFindings 1, 2, 6, and 7 share one root: `query.mountPath` is never validated (no allow-list, canonicalization, or charset bound), and two `exec` sinks build shell strings. The primary chain is unauthenticated->RCE: a remote caller supplies `mountPath`, finding 1 executes immediately, and the captured token (finding 3) plus the second injectable `curl` (finding 6) extend reach to the internal cache endpoint. Finding 5 (swallowed errors) hides exploitation of all of the above, defeating detection. Cross-module: `handler.ts:17` does an unguarded `JSON.parse(req.body)` and `handler.ts:21` routes on attacker-controlled `payload.admin === true` into `processAdmin` -- a privilege-trust gap that, if this layer feeds `getDiskUsage`, supplies the attacker-controlled `DiskQuery` that triggers the RCE chain.\n\n### Missed surfaces (optional)\n\n`handler.ts:21` trusts client-supplied `payload.admin` for an admin branch (A01 privilege escalation) -- outside the 5 scoped findings but a confirmed access-control gap worth a separate review."}],"totalDurationMs":30608,"totalTokens":38231,"totalToolUseCount":2,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2521,"cache_read_input_tokens":34379,"output_tokens":1329,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2521},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"toolStats":{"readCount":2,"searchCount":0,"bashCount":0,"editFileCount":0,"linesAdded":0,"linesRemoved":0,"otherToolCount":0}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01XcvXQ1sS4GzUZouht4jgaF","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"## Security Review Summary\n\nReviewed: `review-src/disk-info.ts` (and sibling `review-src/handler.ts` for cross-module attack-chain coupling)\n\n### Critical\n\n1. `review-src/disk-info.ts:35` [A03] `exec('du -sh ' + path)` concatenates attacker-controlled `query.mountPath` into a shell string; `\"/; rm -rf /\"` yields arbitrary OS command execution. Replace with `execFile('du', ['-sh', path])` plus an allow-list of permitted mount paths.\n3. `review-src/disk-info.ts:20` [A07] live `sk_live_...` key hardcoded in source -- any repo reader, fork, or CI obtains it; unrotatable without code change. Move to a secrets manager / env var and rotate the leaked key now.\n6. `review-src/disk-info.ts:69` [A03] second `exec('curl ' + url + ...)` concatenates the token URL and `JSON.stringify(parsed)` into a shell string (command/argument injection via crafted `du` output). Use `execFile`/`fetch` with an arg array, never a shell string.\n\n### Important\n\n2. `review-src/disk-info.ts:46` [A01] unvalidated `path` passed to `fsSize(path)` enables filesystem traversal (`\"../../etc\"`) outside intended mounts. Canonicalize with `path.resolve` and enforce an allow-list prefix before the sink.\n7. `review-src/disk-info.ts:68` [A02] token sent as query param over `http://cache.internal` -- plaintext on the wire and in proxy/access logs. Switch to `https://` and move the token to an `Authorization` header, not the URL.\n\n### Suggestions\n\n4. `review-src/disk-info.ts:10-15` [A06] `systeminformation@3.42.0` pinned predating command-injection advisories. Unresolved hedge: advisory-affected version (unverified against GHSA/OSV). Verify the specific GHSA/CVE and upgrade to a patched major before committing.\n\n### Questions\n\n5. `review-src/disk-info.ts:58-60` [A09] `catch (_)` in `cacheResult` swallows all errors including exploitation signals; no log/rethrow. Add structured logging. Is there a central log sink this should emit to?\n\n### Threat Patterns\n\nFindings 1, 2, 6, and 7 share one root: `query.mountPath` is never validated (no allow-list, canonicalization, or charset bound), and two `exec` sinks build shell strings. The primary chain is unauthenticated->RCE: a remote caller supplies `mountPath`, finding 1 executes immediately, and the captured token (finding 3) plus the second injectable `curl` (finding 6) extend reach to the internal cache endpoint. Finding 5 (swallowed errors) hides exploitation of all of the above, defeating detection. Cross-module: `handler.ts:17` does an unguarded `JSON.parse(req.body)` and `handler.ts:21` routes on attacker-controlled `payload.admin === true` into `processAdmin` -- a privilege-trust gap that, if this layer feeds `getDiskUsage`, supplies the attacker-controlled `DiskQuery` that triggers the RCE chain.\n\n**Missed surface (outside scoped 5 findings):** `handler.ts:21` trusts client-supplied `payload.admin` for an admin branch [A01 privilege escalation] -- a confirmed access-control gap worth a separate review.\n\n**Verdict scope:** scope: security-threats"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3856,"cache_read_input_tokens":66065,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3856},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d1299fab-aee7-4f65-abd7-c4f2107ff3d0","uuid":"d87fc41a-1ef0-4844-b549-8b8ede36b502","request_id":"req_011CbqYQ7KvmaCL4HbozwBi4"}
